## 2. Problem Statement & Motivation

Financial fraud detection improves dramatically when institutions pool data: fraud rings hit multiple banks, and each bank alone sees only a slice of the pattern. But banks **cannot share raw transaction data** (privacy law, competition, data-residency rules). Federated Learning (FL) solves this: each bank trains locally and shares only model updates.

**The gap FedSpark fills.** Mainstream FL frameworks — Flower, TensorFlow Federated, PySyft, FedML — model a "client" as a single process holding its dataset in memory. That is a cross-*device* assumption (phones). In cross-*silo* FL, one client is an entire organization whose local data is itself a big-data problem: tens of millions of transactions that need distributed storage, distributed feature engineering, and distributed training. Additionally, real transaction data is a **stream**, fraud patterns **drift**, silos are **statistically heterogeneous (non-IID)**, and a compromised silo can **poison** the global model. Existing student-accessible frameworks address none of these together.

**Why Spark specifically (course fit).** Each silo runs Spark for: SQL/window-function feature engineering, Parquet/Delta lakehouse storage, Structured Streaming ingestion from Kafka, and distributed gradient computation via `mapPartitions` + `treeAggregate`. The FL layer is built from scratch on top — no FL framework is imported.

